fields.definition: As Fast As Possible: Perform as quickly as you can.
As Heavy As Possible: Use the heaviest weight you can handle.
As Many Repetitions (or Rounds) As Possible.
Body Weight: Refers to exercises using your own body weight.
The space or gym where CrossFit workouts are performed.
Calories, often used in workouts on machines like rowers or bikes.
Workout with many reps and multiple movements.
Functional, varied movements performed at high intensity.
A person who does CrossFit.
Every Minute on the Minute: Perform a set number of reps each minute.
A grip often used in gymnastics on rings, with wrist resting on the ring.
Focus on quality over speed or weight.
Perform the workout as quickly as possible.
A secure grip for weightlifting, using the thumb as a 'hook'.
Metabolic Conditioning: A workout designed to improve metabolic rate.
Personal Record: Your best performance for a particular movement.
Repetition: One complete movement of an exercise.
A day designated for recovery.
Repetition Maximum: The heaviest weight you can lift for one rep.
Range of Motion: The full movement potential of a joint.
As prescribed: Completing a workout as written, without modifications.
A modified version of a workout or movement to fit an athlete's level.
A specific number of repetitions.
Training focused on improving power and muscle strength.
A workout with 8 rounds of 20 seconds work, 10 seconds rest.
The maximum time allowed to complete a workout.
Unbroken: Completing a set without rest.
Exercises performed before the workout to prepare the body.
Workout of the Day: The main workout prescribed for the day.
Rocking in a 'superman' position.
Back Squat: Squat with the barbell resting on your upper back.
Bench Press: Pressing a barbell while lying on a bench.
Jumping onto a box or platform from a standing position.
Burpee.
Clean: Lifting a weight from the floor to shoulders in one motion.
Clean and Jerk: Lifting the weight to shoulders, then overhead.
Chest to Bar: Pull-up variation where chest must touch the bar.
Deadlift: Lifting a weight from the ground to hip height.
Double Unders: Two rope passes per jump.
Front Squat: Squat with weight held in front of shoulders.
Core movement lying flat on your back with arms and legs elevated.
Handstand Push-Up: Push-up while in a handstand position.
Knees to Elbows: Bringing knees to elbows while hanging from a bar.
Muscle Up: Combination of a pull-up and dip (can be ring or bar).
Overhead Squat: Squat with weight held overhead.
Single-leg squat.
Push Press: Overhead press with a dip in the legs.
Push Jerk: Overhead press with a slight knee bend to catch the bar.
Pull Up or Push Up.
Tricep dips performed on rings.
Climbing a rope with or without leg support.
Sumo Deadlift: Deadlift with wide stance.
Sumo Deadlift High Pull: Sumo deadlift with pull to the chin.
Shoulder Press: Overhead press using only the arms.
Snatch: Lifting weight from floor to overhead in one motion.
Overhead press with a split leg stance.
Squat.
Sit ups or abdominal crunches.
Single Unders: One rope pass per jump.
Lying face down with arms and legs elevated.
Toes to Bar: Bringing toes to touch a bar while hanging.
Core exercise where both hands and feet meet at the top.
Wall Ball Shot: Throwing a weighted ball against a wall.
Pad used under the lumbar spine for ab exercises.
Assault Bike, an air resistance bike.
Olympic lifting bar.
Stationary erg bike.
Dumbbell.
Kettlebell.
Gymnastic rings for bodyweight exercises.
Metal structure for gymnastics exercises.
Rowing machine.
Ski ergometer machine.
